<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-284-924  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 284 924.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  March 26 1990 v24 n13 p90(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Getting by with just the basics. (media conversion services)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Moses, James.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Companies who may feel the pressure to become electronic datainterchange (EDI)-capable have options that satisfy the need butdo not require a substantial systems investment.andP;  Third-partyvendors offer media conversion services that allow companies toreceive EDI messages.andP;  The disadvantage, however, is that theservices do not allow the recipient to send a message.andP;  Anotheroption is to set up a minimal EDI system consisting of a modem, amicrocomputer and a basic translation software package.andO;Translation software allows the exchange of data translated intoan agreed-on format, such as ANSI X12.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Electronic data interchangeCommunications TechnologyThird-Party VendorsCommunications softwareConversionCommunications Modes.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Back to basics: costs of translation software. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>